@BlitzKraft Try running 

``$ which rtv``

and look at the shebang at the top of the file, it should tell you which python runtime is being invoked.

The group widget is set up to use zero-based indexing on that setting, so it should work correctly. In javascript when you use [`.getMonth()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date/getMonth), it returns a zero-based index value, so that is why it is set up that way.

If you share the code you are using, I could help; but the basic solution is to take whatever month one-based index you have and subtract one. Something like this:

```js
var user_selected_month = 12,
  months = [ "Jan", "Fev", "Mar", "Abr", "Mai", "Jun", "Jul", "Ago", "Set", "Out", "Nov", "Dez" ];

alert( months[ user_selected_month - 1 ] );
```

Hi @hatimhaidry!

Get the [`config` variable](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#config) for the table, then check the [`config.totalRows` value](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#variable-totalrows). I set up [this demo](https://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/ft3qyjns/12/) for you.

```js
$(function() {
	function showRows(table) {
  	alert('The tbody has ' + table.config.totalRows + ' rows');
  }
  $('table').tablesorter({
    widgets: ['scroller'],
    initialized: showRows
  });
});
```

