@caspervdw, that's a very good point about `memory`. That might be a simple way to address the "glitch" scenario that will work for most users of `link_df()`. I'm starting to see that it makes sense for `link_df()` to be strict about successive integer (or rounded float) frame numbers. Maybe it could issue a warning the first time it encounters an empty frame?

(The reason I say "rounded float" is that there are plenty of ways to represent/store tracks data that prohibit mixing types. So I don't think trackpy should ever be strict about the dtype of `frame` unless absolutely necessary.)

To me, the underlying problem is that when features data are passed as a single DataFrame, there is no way to denote an empty frame.  `link_df_iter()` does not have this problem. If you want the empty frame to be considered, include it in the sequence; if you want it to be skipped over, don't (and leave a 2*t* gap in the frame numbers). So I don't see how `expected_frames` does anything but add complication. If we still think it's a good functionality to have in trackpy, maybe we could add a separate function that pre-processes input to `link_df_iter()`.

