A preview of the `dispatch` decorator is on the `develop` branch of PyEcore and PyEcore-py2. It still misses the documentation, but you can use it like this (for a metamodel containing `A` and `B` metaclasses):

```python
from pyecore.dispatch import dispatch

# Switch definition
class MySwitch(object):
    @dispatch
    def do_switch(self, o):
        print('In default case')

    @do_switch.register(A)
    def caseA(self, o):
        print('Case', o.eClass.name)

    @do_switch.register(B)
    def caseB(self, o):
        print(Case for B instances', o) 


# let say that we have a 'root', and we want to iterate on every children
# 'eAllContent()' produces a generator
switcher = MySwitch()
for child in root.eAllContents():
    switcher.do_switch(child)
````

Currently, there is no restriction on the default function name. This would have interesting for `ComposedSwitch`, but as the switch does not bring the same constraints has EMF, it seems that a `ComposedSwitch` would not be necessary .
